INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '64b405d2-7471-46a2-ba93-bc90130faf58',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Vue Feature-Based Folder Structure — Colocation & Barrel Exports Done Right$escape$,
  $escape$Grouping Vue files by type (`/components`, `/composables`, `/stores`) breaks down fast once your app grows. Feature-based structure colocates everything a domain owns: its components, composables, Pinia stores, and route definitions live together under `/features/auth/`, `/features/dashboard/`, etc.

Each feature folder gets an `index.ts` barrel that controls its public API. Only what's exported from `index.ts` is fair game for other features — internals stay private by convention. This prevents cross-feature spaghetti imports like `../../features/auth/components/LoginForm.vue`.

Vue Router's lazy-loading pairs naturally here: `component: () => import('@/features/dashboard/pages/DashboardPage.vue')` keeps each feature's bundle chunk self-contained. Pinia stores defined inside the feature folder stay scoped — no global store sprawl. Composables like `useAuth()` exported from the barrel mean consumers never care about the internal file layout. When a feature grows too large, you split it into sub-features without touching any external import paths — the barrel absorbs the restructure.$escape$,
  $escape$// features/auth/index.ts — the public API contract
export { default as LoginForm } from './components/LoginForm.vue'
export { default as useAuth } from './composables/useAuth'
export { useAuthStore } from './stores/authStore'

// router/index.ts — lazy-loaded, chunk per feature
{
  path: '/login',
  component: () => import('@/features/auth/pages/LoginPage.vue')
}

// Another feature consuming auth — only via barrel
import { useAuth } from '@/features/auth'$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
