INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '5ce1d500-f20c-4831-930c-b9301fcd0cb4',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Vue 3 — Prop Typing with Discriminated Unions for Variant Components$escape$,
  $escape$Vue 3's `defineProps` with TypeScript generics lets you enforce exhaustive prop contracts at compile time. For a Button component with multiple visual variants, a plain `type: String` prop silently accepts garbage values. Instead, use a discriminated union via `PropType<T>` or the type-only `defineProps<{}>` syntax to lock variants down.

With the script setup + TypeScript combo, you skip `PropType` entirely — just declare an inline type. For conditional slot behavior or computed classes that branch on variant, TypeScript narrows the union automatically inside `if` checks, eliminating `any` casts and runtime guards.

Avoid `defineProps({ variant: String })` — it gives you `string | undefined` with zero narrowing. The type-safe path is `defineProps<{ variant: 'primary' | 'danger' | 'ghost' }>()`, which Vue's compiler transforms into runtime validator metadata automatically. Pair this with `withDefaults` to set a fallback without losing the union constraint.$escape$,
  $escape$<script setup lang="ts">
type Variant = 'primary' | 'danger' | 'ghost'

const props = withDefaults(
  defineProps<{
    variant: Variant
    disabled?: boolean
  }>(),
  { variant: 'primary', disabled: false }
)

const classes = computed(() => ({
  'btn-primary': props.variant === 'primary',
  'btn-danger':  props.variant === 'danger',
  'btn-ghost':   props.variant === 'ghost',
}))
</script>$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
