INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '2e701562-421d-46c8-8c30-b7c319a5bfc7',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Vue Error Boundaries — Per-Route Error, Loading, and Empty State Handling$escape$,
  $escape$Vue 3 lacks React-style error boundaries natively, but `onErrorCaptured` in a wrapper component gives you the same control per route. Define a `RouteShell.vue` that each route's layout uses — it captures descendant errors, exposes a loading slot driven by the router's navigation guard, and renders an empty state when data resolves to null or an empty array.

Use `defineAsyncComponent` with its built-in `loadingComponent` and `errorComponent` options for code-split route chunks — this handles the async import lifecycle without custom logic. For data-fetching errors, pair `onErrorCaptured` (returning `false` to stop propagation) with a reactive `error` ref. Pass `suspense: true` on async components to coordinate with `<Suspense>` boundaries, letting you co-locate the fallback UI with the feature rather than scattering try/catch across composables.

Empty state is the easiest to miss: always check `data.value?.length === 0` separately from `data.value === null` — the first means the fetch succeeded but returned nothing; the second means it hasn't resolved yet.$escape$,
  $escape$<!-- RouteShell.vue -->
<script setup lang="ts">
import { ref, onErrorCaptured } from 'vue'

const error = ref<Error | null>(null)
const props = defineProps<{ loading: boolean; empty: boolean }>()

onErrorCaptured((err) => {
  error.value = err
  return false // stop propagation
})
</script>

<template>
  <div v-if="error">Something went wrong: {{ error.message }}</div>
  <div v-else-if="props.loading">Loading...</div>
  <div v-else-if="props.empty">No results found.</div>
  <slot v-else />
</template>$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
