INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '073ea670-c47e-4a4d-82cd-f196284dc5d2',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Vue Accessibility — Semantic HTML First, ARIA Only When HTML Falls Short$escape$,
  $escape$Vue's component model makes it easy to build `<div>`-heavy UIs that screen readers can't navigate. Start with semantic HTML: `<button>` for actions, `<nav>` for navigation, `<main>` for page content. Vue doesn't change this contract.

For focus management, use `ref` on elements and call `.focus()` after state transitions — e.g., move focus to a modal's first interactive element when `v-if` renders it. Use `nextTick` so the DOM is ready before focusing.

Avoid ARIA until native HTML genuinely can't express the pattern. A `<button>` doesn't need `role="button"`. A `<select>` doesn't need `aria-expanded`. Where ARIA is justified — custom comboboxes, live regions — bind attributes dynamically: `:aria-expanded="isOpen"`, `:aria-live="polite"`.

For route changes in Vue Router, announce navigation with a visually-hidden live region updated in the `afterEach` hook. Vue's reactivity makes this a single `ref` update. Scoped slots in UI library components (Headless UI, Radix Vue) handle most ARIA plumbing — prefer them over hand-rolling.$escape$,
  $escape$<!-- ModalDialog.vue -->
<template>
  <div v-if="open" role="dialog" aria-modal="true" :aria-labelledby="titleId">
    <h2 :id="titleId" ref="titleRef">{{ title }}</h2>
    <slot />
    <button @click="$emit('close')">Close</button>
  </div>
</template>

<script setup lang="ts">
import { ref, watch, nextTick } from 'vue'

const props = defineProps<{ open: boolean; title: string; titleId: string }>()
const titleRef = ref<HTMLElement | null>(null)

watch(() => props.open, async (val) => {
  if (val) {
    await nextTick()
    titleRef.value?.focus()
  }
})
</script>$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
