INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '320be85a-08b3-43bc-a0ba-64a019cc5589',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Vue Quality Gates — Prettier, Husky + lint-staged, and tsc --noEmit That Actually Catch Bugs$escape$,
  $escape$Vue 3 projects using Vite and TypeScript ship with `vue-tsc` — not plain `tsc` — because template type-checking requires the Vue language plugin. Running `vue-tsc --noEmit` in CI catches broken prop types and missing emits that your editor might silently ignore. Wire it into GitHub Actions as a separate step so it fails fast before tests run.

For pre-commit hygiene, `lint-staged` should scope Prettier to `.vue`, `.ts`, and `.js` files — but pass `--parser babel` only for `.js`; Vue SFCs need `--parser vue` or they'll strip `<template>` formatting. Husky v9 uses the new `husky init` flow: no `.huskyrc`, just shell files in `.husky/`.

Critical gotcha: `eslint-plugin-vue` rules like `vue/no-undef-components` won't fire unless `parserOptions.parser` is set to `@typescript-eslint/parser` inside your flat config — skipping this means component registration errors pass lint silently.$escape$,
  $escape$# .husky/pre-commit
npx lint-staged

# lint-staged.config.mjs
export default {
  '*.{ts,tsx}': ['eslint --fix', 'prettier --write'],
  '*.vue': ['eslint --fix', 'prettier --parser vue --write'],
  '*.js': ['prettier --parser babel --write'],
};

# .github/workflows/ci.yml (relevant step)
- name: Type-check Vue templates
  run: npx vue-tsc --noEmit$escape$,
